   721	In all the foregoing discussions, the idea has been implicit that the
   722	$\langle f_k \rangle$ on which we base our probability distributions
   723	represent the results of measurements of various quantities. If the
   724	energy is included among the $f_k$, the resulting equations are
   725	identical with those of conventional statistical mechanics. However, in
   726	practice a measurement of energy is rarely part of the initial
   727	information available; it is the temperature that is easily measurable.
   728	In order to treat the experimental measurement of temperature from the
   729	present point of view, it is necessary to consider not only the system
   730	$\sigma_1$ under investigation, but also another system $\sigma_2$. We
   731	introduce several definitions: A *heat bath* is a system $\sigma_2$ such
   732	that (a) The separation of energy levels of $\sigma_2$ is much smaller
   733	than any macroscopically measurable energy difference, so that the
   734	possible energies $E_{2j}$ form, from the macroscopic point of view, a
   735	continuum. (b) The entropy $S_2$ of the maximum-entropy probability
   736	distribution for given $\langle E_2 \rangle$ is a definite monotonic
   737	function of $\langle E_2 \rangle$; i.e., $\sigma_2$ contains no
   738	"mechanical parameters" which can be varied independently of its
   739	energy. (c) $\sigma_2$ can be placed in interaction with another system
