   940	case of higher spin values.
   941	## Conclusion
   942	The essential point in the arguments presented above is that we accept
   943	the von-Neumann-Shannon expression for entropy, very literally, as a
   944	measure of the amount of uncertainty represented by a probability
   945	distribution; thus entropy becomes the primitive concept with which we
   946	work, more fundamental even than energy. If in addition we reinterpret
   947	the prediction problem of statistical mechanics in the subjective sense,
   948	we can derive the usual relations in a very elementary way without any
   949	consideration of ensembles or appeal to the usual arguments concerning
   950	ergodicity or equal *a priori* probabilities. The principles and
   951	mathematical methods of statistical mechanics are seen to be of much
   952	[^19]M. B. Lewis and A. J. F. Siegert, Phys. Rev. 101, 1227 (1956).
   953	more general applicability than conventional arguments would lead one to
   954	suppose. In the problem of prediction, the maximization of entropy is
   955	not an application of a law of physics, but merely a method of reasoning
   956	which ensures that no unconscious arbitrary assumptions have been
   957	introduced.
   958	## Appendix A. Entropy of a Probability Distribution {#appendix-a.-entropy-of-a-probability-distribution .unnumbered}
   959	The variable $x$ can assume the discrete values $(x_1, \dots, x_n)$. Our
